---
// /privacy — privacy policy for the mitos.run marketing + docs site. Reflects
// what this STATIC site actually does today (no analytics, no accounts, a
// client-side GitHub star fetch). Review with counsel before relying on it.
// Update the data practices here if the hosted console or analytics ship.
import Site from '../layouts/Site.astro';

const GITHUB = 'https://github.com/mitos-run/mitos';
const UPDATED = 'June 22, 2026';
const TITLE = 'Privacy Policy: what mitos.run collects';
const DESC =
  'How mitos.run handles data: consent-based, EU-hosted analytics (PostHog), no accounts, and nothing tracked until you opt in.';
---

<Site title={TITLE} description={DESC}>
  <section class="page-hero container">
    <p class="eyebrow mono">Legal</p>
    <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>
    <p class="lede">What this site collects, and the consent-based analytics you can turn off.</p>
    <p class="updated mono">Last updated: {UPDATED}</p>
  </section>

  <section class="container prose">
    <p>
      This policy covers <strong>mitos.run</strong>, the marketing and documentation site for the
      mitos project. It is a static website with no user accounts and no sign-up. It uses one
      privacy-friendly, EU-hosted analytics tool, and <strong>only after you opt in</strong>: no
      analytics cookies are set and no analytics data is collected unless you choose "Accept" on the
      consent banner. When a hosted product is added, this policy will be updated before that ships.
    </p>

    <h2>What we collect</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Nothing through forms.</strong> There are no contact forms, sign-ups, or accounts on
      this site today, so we do not ask for or store your name, email, or other personal details.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Analytics, only with your consent.</strong> If you accept analytics, we use
      <strong>PostHog</strong>, processed in the European Union, to understand which pages are
      useful. It is configured for privacy: client IP addresses are discarded, session replays are
      captured with every form input masked (so typed values are never recorded), and we never
      identify you (analytics are anonymous and not linked to a person). If
      you decline, or never choose, PostHog is not loaded and nothing is sent. You can change your
      choice anytime via "Cookie settings" in the footer.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Standard server logs.</strong> The site is served by GitHub Pages, which may process
      standard request data (such as IP address and user agent) to deliver the site and protect it
      from abuse, under GitHub's own privacy practices.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>GitHub star count.</strong> To show a live count of GitHub stars, your browser makes a
      request directly to GitHub's public API. That request is handled by GitHub under its privacy
      statement. We cache the returned number in your browser's local storage purely to avoid
      repeat requests; it is not personal data and never leaves your device.
    </p>

    <h2>Cookies and local storage</h2>
    <p>
      Until you opt in to analytics, we set <strong>no cookies</strong>. By default the only browser
      storage used is a local-storage entry caching the GitHub star count, plus a record of your
      analytics choice. If you accept analytics, PostHog stores a cookie and local-storage entries to
      count visits. Decline, or change your mind via "Cookie settings" in the footer, and these are
      not set. You can also clear them from your browser at any time.
    </p>

    <h2>Sub-processors</h2>
    <p>For the operation of this site we rely on:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GitHub, Inc.</strong> hosting (GitHub Pages) and the public GitHub API used for the star count.</li>
      <li><strong>Cloudflare, Inc.</strong> CDN and edge security in front of the site (processes request traffic).</li>
      <li><strong>PostHog</strong> product analytics and masked session replay, processed in the European Union, <strong>only if you opt in</strong>. IP addresses are discarded and every form input is masked.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The open-source engine you run yourself does not send data to us. If you later use a hosted
      mitos product, its data processing will be described in that product's terms and a data
      processing agreement, separate from this site policy.
    </p>

    <h2>Your choices</h2>
    <p>
      Analytics are off until you opt in, and you can withdraw consent at any time via "Cookie
      settings" in the footer, which stops collection. Because analytics are anonymous, processed in
      the EU, and stripped of IP addresses, the data is not tied to you personally. For questions
      about GitHub's or Cloudflare's processing of requests to their services, see their respective
      privacy statements.
    </p>

    <h2>Changes</h2>
    <p>
      We will update this page if our data practices change and revise the date above. Material
      changes will be reflected here before they take effect.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      Questions about this policy can be raised through the channels on our
      <a href="/contact">contact page</a> or the project
      <a href={GITHUB} target="_blank" rel="noopener">repository</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</Site>

<style>
  .page-hero { position: relative; }
  .updated { color: var(--ink-3); font-size: 13px; margin-top: 8px; }
  .prose { max-width: 52em; padding-bottom: 96px; }
  .prose p { color: var(--ink-2); font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0 0 18px; }
  .prose ul { color: var(--ink-2); font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0 0 18px; padding-left: 22px; }
  .prose li { margin: 0 0 8px; }
  .prose strong { color: var(--ink); font-weight: 500; }
  .prose a { color: var(--cyan); border-bottom: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cyan) 30%, transparent); }
  .prose a:hover { border-bottom-color: var(--cyan); }
  .prose h2 { font-size: clamp(20px, 2.4vw, 26px); font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: var(--track-display); margin: 36px 0 12px; }
</style>
